To find the rank of matrix A, we need to perform Gaussian elimination to find the row echelon form of the matrix and then count the number of non-zero rows.

Matrix A:
\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 4 & 8 \\ 1 & 0 & 3 \\ 3 & 6 & 0 \end{bmatrix}

First, we will swap Row 1 and Row 2 to have a 1 in the top left corner:

\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 3 \\ 2 & 4 & 8 \\ 3 & 6 & 0 \end{bmatrix}

Now, we will eliminate the elements below the 1 in the top left corner. To do this, we will perform the following row operations:

Row 2 = Row 2 - 2 * Row 1
Row 3 = Row 3 - 3 * Row 1

\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 3 \\ 0 & 4 & 2 \\ 0 & 6 & -9 \end{bmatrix}

Next, we will divide Row 2 by 4 to get a leading 1 in the second row:

\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 3 \\ 0 & 1 & 1/2 \\ 0 & 6 & -9 \end{bmatrix}

Now, we will eliminate the element below the 1 in the second row. To do this, we will perform the following row operation:

Row 3 = Row 3 - 6 * Row 2

\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 3 \\ 0 & 1 & 1/2 \\ 0 & 0 & -12 \end{bmatrix}

Finally, we will divide Row 3 by -12 to get a leading 1 in the third row:

\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 3 \\ 0 & 1 & 1/2 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}

Now, we have the row echelon form of matrix A. Since all rows are non-zero, the rank of matrix A is 3.
